@SarahGlaser9 I don't think the gateway to reading is spelling. A child can be taught to read without ever spelling a single word. 

The gateway to reading is knowledge of grapheme-phoneme correspondences and the skill of blending.

David Share calls this the "sine qua non" of reading,

@debbiehepp @RyonWLeyshon @JasmineFS208 @SusanGodsland Your last sentence sums it up perfectly Debbie.

To teach reading is to teach a child how to go from print to sound. (How else could Share's self-teaching occur?)

Spelling is the skill that goes from sound to print.

@SusanGodsland @JasmineFS208 @debbiehepp Let me re-phrase it.

Your statement using the word "all" seems too categorical to me, given there are many quality SSP programs that are organized around letters rather than sounds. 

This is not a battle reformers should be wanting to fight.

@SusanGodsland @JasmineFS208 @debbiehepp "All high quality SSP programs are organised around the sounds." 

I think that statement indicates "McGuinness Syndrome," a condition that that causes a "my way or the highway" mentality.

IMHO, quality SSP programs can be organized either way.

@debbiehepp @EdInspire @KirstenDuncombe @lifelonglit I agree with Debbie. It's not until the "Emerald" level (Grade 4 to Grade 5) that it says, under Decoding: "Illustrations provide less support for decoding."

Decoding should never depend on illustrations in the first place.

Not a synthetic program.

